Speaking about the visuals I am not so happy. It may be cool that this mag also runs well on an Amiga 500 but if the price is that we have to watch at a more or less ugly design, then the price is too high. At least for me. That may be different for other people. It's just my personal view. And we should not forget how less people do exist that only own an oldskool Amiga, but none of the fresher models. Does µC5VoidµC4 really reach that high number of additional readers by making it possible to read it on an A500?? I guess that is not the case. Using a higher number of colours for the panels should not cut down the number of readers, but could be a lot more pleasing if the graphician knows well what he is doing.

Instead of using typical smooth diskmag tunes µC5RumrunnerµC4 decided to pick out three chiptunes. Well, really not usual for a mag but still acceptable. The module of issue one, which was also tracked by µC5RumrunnerµC4 was much more worse, the three chiptumes were really okay to listen at. Especially the first one was cute and sounded like the old school aswell.

But what is a mag worth without good articles? And this time everybody should be satisfied with the result of the editors work. µC5Saxonia#2µC4 has everything a good mag should offer. Opinion articles, private views & stories, general articles, a short interview. And this time performed by a higher number of supporters.

